snippet.textDisplay:
Nate round 3, and edged round 5. Round 4 was pivotal and Connor took it. Looked like Nate was a little tired and the blood in his eyes bothered him enough to slow him down. Connor's boxing when everyone is 100% is a grade above Diaz. But Diaz is so tough and has enough cardio to soak up the damage and tire out his opponent's skill and reflexes.
I'm not sure there is a tougher fighter in the game than Diaz in terms of straight up taking damage and getting in his opponents face regardless of what they hit them with.
Connor showed he has the spirit of champion when he came back in the 4th and 5th after looking spent and battered in the 3rd.
snippet.textOriginal:
Nate round 3, and edged round 5.  Round 4 was pivotal and Connor took it.  Looked like Nate was a little tired and the blood in his eyes bothered him enough to slow him down.  Connor's boxing when everyone is 100% is a grade above Diaz.  But Diaz is so tough and has enough cardio to soak up the damage and tire out his opponent's skill and reflexes.
  I'm not sure there is a tougher fighter in the game than Diaz in terms of straight up taking damage and getting in his opponents face regardless of what they hit them with.
Connor showed he has the spirit of champion when he came back in the 4th and 5th after looking spent and battered in the 3rd.

snippet.textDisplay: Mcgregor is incredible, as was Diaz, however, surely this would have been a foregone conclusion had Connor not started to run out of steam late in the second round; until then he was obliterating Diaz. While not a UFC fight expert, I do know about conditioning and high-intensity training can condition you to keep up the intensity Mcgregor brings to the ring. Before this fight I honestly thought we had seen the best of Connor, but, I am not so sure now, especially if he addresses this point. Any world-class athlete (in aerobic sports) should be able to do 5 sets of 5 minutes of intense exercise with a minute break between each.
